  "prompt": "How do flu vaccines work?",
  "response": "Flu vaccines work by stimulating the immune system to produce an immune response to the influenza virus without causing the illness. Here's a step-by-step explanation of how they function:\n\n1. **Antigen Introduction**: The vaccine contains antigens, which are parts of the virus that the immune system recognizes as foreign. These antigens can be inactivated (killed) virus, pieces of the virus (like surface proteins), or a weakened (attenuated) form of the virus that cannot cause illness.\n\n2. **Immune System Activation**: When the vaccine is administered, the antigens are introduced into the body. The immune system identifies these antigens as foreign invaders and begins to respond.\n\n3. **Recognition and Response**: The immune system recognizes these specific antigens and produces antibodies, which are specialized proteins that can neutralize or destroy the virus.\n\n4. **Memory Cells Formation**: In addition to producing antibodies, the immune system also creates memory cells. These cells \"remember\" the specific antigens of the influenza virus.\n\n5. **Future Protection**: If the person is later exposed to the actual flu virus, their immune system can quickly recognize and attack the virus, preventing or reducing the severity of the illness. The memory cells facilitate a rapid and robust immune response.\n\n**Types of Flu Vaccines**:\n- **Inactivated or Recombinant Vaccines**: These contain killed virus particles or proteins from the virus. They cannot cause the flu but still prompt an immune response.\n- **Live Attenuated Influenza Vaccine (LAIV)**: This contains a weakened form of the virus. It is designed to cause a mild or asymptomatic infection that still stimulates the immune system without causing full-blown flu.\n- **mRNA Vaccines**: These use messenger RNA to instruct cells to produce a protein that triggers an immune response. mRNA flu vaccines are a newer development and were inspired by the technology used in some COVID-19 vaccines.\n\n**Seasonal Adaptation**:\n- The composition of flu vaccines is reviewed and updated annually to match the strains of influenza virus that are expected to be most prevalent in the upcoming flu season. This is because the flu virus mutates frequently, leading to different strains circulating each year.\n\n**Effectiveness**:\n- The effectiveness of flu vaccines can vary each year depending on how well the vaccine's antigens match the circulating flu strains. Despite this variability, vaccination remains the best method to reduce the risk of flu and its complications.\n\nBy getting vaccinated, individuals not only protect themselves but also contribute to herd immunity, reducing the overall spread of the virus in the community.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
